<div class="nucleosomes-heading-text">
        <p
          style="
            color: #222720 !important;
            max-width: 985px;
            text-align: left;
            padding-bottom: 1rem;
          "
        >
          Histone post-translational modifications (PTMs) play crucial roles in
          chromatin regulation, interacting with a wide array of enzymes, reader
          proteins, and multi-subunit complexes to coordinate downstream
          processes. Historically, modified histone peptides have been the
          favored substrate for
          <em>in vitro</em> chromatin studies, under the assumption that PTMs
          are unaffected by higher order nucleosome structure.
          <strong
            >However, recent work from EpiCypher points to an integral role for
            nucleosome conformation in dictating histone PTM interactions and
            chromatin function (<a
              href="https://www.biorxiv.org/content/10.1101/2022.02.21.481373v1"
              target="_blank"
              >Marunde et al. 2022</a
            >;
            <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34819353/" target="_blank"
              >Morgan et al. 2021</a
            >)</strong
          >.
        </p>

        <p
          style="
            color: #222720 !important;
            max-width: 985px;
            text-align: left;
            padding-bottom: 1rem;
          "
        >
          EpiCypher offers a diverse array of
          <a href="/recombinant-nucleosomes-complete-list/"
            >recombinant nucleosomes
          </a>
          carrying various histone PTMs, histone variants, oncogenic mutations,
          and more. We also offer
          <a href="/services/custom-nucleosome-development"
            >custom nucleosome development services</a
          >
          and
          <a
            href="/services/dcypher-assay-services-for-novel-chromatin-interactions"
            >dCypher screening services</a
          >
          for specialized research projects and studying chromatin interactions.
          The use of nucleosome substrates is essential to generate accurate,
          physiological data, and are highly recommended compared to histone
          peptides (see <strong>Figure</strong> below). However, if you would
          like to still obtain histone peptides, or are interested in the
          peptides we used to sell, you can contact the 
          <a
            href="https://www.med.unc.edu/csb/unc-peptides/histone-peptides/"
            target="_blank"
            >UNC Peptide Core Facility</a
          > that specializes in custom histone peptide synthesis.
        </p>

